object.Paragraph1: A field type for data that is complex, nested, and has a custom data schema.
object.Paragraph2: You can design your own data model schema by using object field type.

string.Paragraph1: A text field for simple, short and unformatted texts. The string field displays a input that can contain small text. This field can be used for titles, names, descriptions, etc.
string.Paragraph2: This field is best used for simple text data and basic single-line text content that doesn’t need special styling or formatting like headings, inline styles, or inline media like images or video.
string.CommonUses3: Short-form text that doesn’t need any styling

integer.Paragraph1: A whole number. The integer field displays a field for integer values.

float.Paragraph1: A decimal number. The float field displays a field for decimal values.

boolean.Paragraph1: A switch field for values that have two states, e.g. yes or no, true or false, exist or not-exist etc.
boolean.Paragraph2: The boolean field displays a toggle button or check box to manage boolean values.

array.Paragraph1: A collection type for a list of values. Fields can contain multiple values with the array type. An array can contain values by all field types.

tags.Paragraph1: A collection type for a list of words.

enum.Paragraph1: The enumeration field allows to configure a list of values displayed in a drop-down list.
enum.Paragraph2: Creates a list of predefined values so you can pick one for each collection item.
enum.Paragraph3: Use an enum field when you want editors to choose a value from a list of predefined values, which will be presented in a dropdown when they create their collection items. You can define these values in the enum field settings.

const.Paragraph1: A field type for constant values. Use a const field when you want to describe a constant.
const.Paragraph2: The constant fields are read-only. The value of that fields can not be changed on contents.
const.CommonUses1: All fixed value scenarios needed in content

json.Paragraph1: The json field allows to configure data in a JSON format, to store JSON objects or arrays. Use for storing any other irregular types of objects you have defined.
json.Paragraph2: A json field is not stored as a string value. They are directly stored as object instances.
json.CommonUses1: Data models without a specific schema

date.Paragraph1: A date field in ISO 8601 format. The date field can display a date (year, month, day) picker.
date.Paragraph2: The date field is support just date values (year, month, day). If you need time resolution, use datetime field type.
date.CommonUses1: A date in the future (upcoming event, release date, etc)
date.CommonUses2: A date in the past (birthday, historical date, etc)

datetime.Paragraph1: A date and time in ISO 8601 format. The date field can display a date (year, month, day), time (hour, minute, second) or datetime (year, month, day, hour, minute, and second) picker.
datetime.Paragraph2: This field allows you to create both a date and time field, which will display itself as a date picker for editors when creating an item in this content type.
datetime.CommonUses1: A date or time in the future (upcoming event, release date, etc)
datetime.CommonUses2: A date or time in the past (birthday, historical date, etc)

longtext.Paragraph1: A long text field for paragraphs of text.
longtext.Paragraph2: This field is best used for basic multi-line text or longer text that will have many lines that doesn’t need special styling or formatting like headings, inline styles, or inline media.
longtext.CommonUses2: Long text that doesn’t need any styling

richtext.Paragraph1: The rich text field displays an editor with formatting options to manage rich text. This field can be used for long written content.
richtext.Paragraph2: The rich-text field is made for long-form content, like a blog post. It allows editors to customize styling and add in headings, paragraphs, and media like images and videos right inside this one field.

email.Paragraph1: The Email field displays an email address field with format validation to ensure the email address is valid.

uri.Paragraph1: The uri field displays an uri or address field with format validation to ensure the url is valid.

hostname.Paragraph1: The hostname field displays an hostname field with format validation to ensure the hostname is valid.

color.Paragraph1: Adds a unique color which can be applied as text color, background color, or border color etc. in your designs.
color.CommonUses4: All styling needs that need a color value

location.Paragraph1: Coordinate values for storing the latitude and longitude of a location.
location.CommonUses2: A flag point on the map

reference.Paragraph1: A link to another entry, content, content group or dataset. The reference field allows to establish a relation with another content-type.
reference.Paragraph2: You can choose single, multiple or dataset as the relation type.

code.Paragraph1: A field for programming or scripting language code. You can create and manage code blocks in an integrated editor using the below languages.
code.Paragraph2: apex, azcli, bat, c, clojure, coffeescript, c++, c#, csp, css, dockerfile, fsharp, go, graphql, handlebars, html, ini, java, javascript, json, kotlin, less, lua, markdown, msdax, mysql, objective-c, pascal, perl, pgsql, php, plaintext, postiats, powerquery, powershell, pug, python, r, razor, redis, redshift, ruby, rust, sb, scheme, scss, shell, sol, sql, st, swift, tcl, typescript, vb, xml, yaml

image.Paragraph1: The image field. You can add a single image or an image collection to your contents.
image.Paragraph2: You can choose an image file from your file storage or you can upload a new image file.

video.Paragraph1: The video field. You can add a video for your contents.
video.Paragraph2: You can choose an video file from your file storage or you can upload a new video file.

nestedType.Paragraph1: You can manage your data in nested form with parent/child relations with nested type fields.
nestedType.Paragraph2: You can use the models you created from the nested types menu as a field in your content.

photoGallery.Paragraph1: With this field type, you can create photo galleries with fields such as title, description, body text, etc.

Search.BoostDescription: The factor used to decrease or increase the relevance scores of a query. It's 1.0 as default. You can use the boost parameter to adjust relevance scores for searches containing two or more queries. A boost value between 0 and 1.0 decreases the relevance score. A value greater than 1.0 increases the relevance score.
Search.SlopDescription: The slop parameter tells the search query how many allowed extra words are between your phrase terms.
Search.FuzzinessDescription: The fuzzy queries help in case of typos etc by adjusting the level of similarity that can be obtained according to changes in the letter order in search terms using the Levenshtein algorithm.
Search.PrefixLengthDescription: Prefix length is the number of prefix characters that is not considered in fuzzy query. In a fuzzy query, similarity in terms is not searched for characters as much as the number of the prefix length. As the prefix length increases, the similarity set will narrow, but the query performance will increase.
Search.MaxExpansionsDescription: The max expansions parameter defines the maximum number of terms the fuzzy query will match before halting the search. Basically, it means that under the hood in one step when the search engine is triggering a fuzzy query it is limiting the number of terms considered in the search to the max expansions.
Search.OperatorDescription: It defines the logical operator between the search expressions.
Search.MinimumShouldMatchDescription: Specifies at least how many of the terms in the query the search results should match.
